    {
      "id": "e2ddec19d7e132b018758f05968dae8e20d972d9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-06-21 06:52:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(13 inline comments)\n\nUnfortunately, I don't really understand the reason that the order of all these checks was changed.  Can you please explain, and perhaps document, the order that you are putting the checks in?\n\nCombining the changes to the checks along with moving the code around makes the patch very difficult to inspect, and in at least one place (OBD_CONNECT_*) there were some errors in the changes.\n\nIf it is necessary to move the functions around, I would suggest one patch that is fixing the checks, and a second patch that is ONLY moving the functions around without any changes.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "8687c26a685c2ac050f355cc83c80397bac783ad",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 118,
        "name": "Mikhail Pershin",
        "email": "mpershin@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "tappro"
      },
      "date": "2011-06-21 08:54:47.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nAndreas, the only wirecheck.c is changed by hand, IIRC. Then wiretests are generated by make -C lustre/utils newwiretest.\nSee comment in lustre_assert_wire_constants() about that.\nTherefore it makes sense to inspect only wirecheck changes there.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
